The sea levels are rising.

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.830 align:middle line:84%
Multiple forest fires on
multiple continents raging out

00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:02.480 align:middle line:90%
of controls.

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:03.892 align:middle line:90%
Disease with no medical cure.

00:16:03.892 --> 00:16:05.600 align:middle line:84%
Hundreds of millions
of people are dying.

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:06.450 align:middle line:90%
Many war fronts.

00:16:06.450 --> 00:16:09.210 align:middle line:84%
And we also know there are a lot
of really good things happening

00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:10.580 align:middle line:90%
in this planet right now.

00:16:10.580 --> 00:16:12.900 align:middle line:84%
There's a new world
that is emerging

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:16.070 align:middle line:84%
in the midst of the
chaos of the world that

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:18.070 align:middle line:90%
is no longer sustainable.

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:20.770 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's so
important just to say this.

00:16:20.770 --> 00:16:22.720 align:middle line:84%
Not one of the
indigenous traditions,

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:25.670 align:middle line:84%
at least that I'm aware of,
has ever said specifically

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:26.800 align:middle line:90%
that our world will end.

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.950 align:middle line:84%
They've all said
we have a choice.

00:16:28.950 --> 00:16:31.490 align:middle line:84%
And the dark ending that's
the focus of the media

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:32.480 align:middle line:90%
is one possibility.

00:16:32.480 --> 00:16:35.750 align:middle line:84%
There's another possibility
because we could just as easily

00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:38.500 align:middle line:84%
say this is the beginning of
a new cycle, the beginning

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:39.300 align:middle line:90%
of a new world age.

00:16:39.300 --> 00:16:40.490 align:middle line:84%
But people like
to talk about ends

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:41.570 align:middle line:90%
more than they do beginnings.

00:16:41.570 --> 00:16:42.236 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Exactly.

00:16:42.236 --> 00:16:43.980 align:middle line:84%
And because the
beginning has to do

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:46.435 align:middle line:90%
with us unfolding our hearts.

00:16:46.435 --> 00:16:47.310 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: I think so.

00:16:47.310 --> 00:16:47.590 align:middle line:84%
That's precisely where
we're going with this.

00:16:47.590 --> 00:16:49.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it's not
as sexy in the media

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:50.940 align:middle line:90%
to be talking about that, yes.

00:16:50.940 --> 00:16:52.979 align:middle line:84%
It is an inner journey
where we're going.

00:16:52.979 --> 00:16:54.520 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I think
you're right, Lisa.

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:56.019 align:middle line:84%
And so what I'd
like to do, I'd like

00:16:56.019 --> 00:16:59.380 align:middle line:84%
to share with you, with
our viewers-- the science.

00:16:59.380 --> 00:17:01.380 align:middle line:84%
And science doesn't mean
it has to be technical.

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:03.700 align:middle line:84%
Science just means
these are proven facts.

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:06.272 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to share them
in a very non-technical way.

00:17:06.272 --> 00:17:07.730 align:middle line:84%
I think our listeners
probably know

00:17:07.730 --> 00:17:09.569 align:middle line:84%
that there's a
history of our planet

00:17:09.569 --> 00:17:11.960 align:middle line:84%
that's locked in the
ice cores or in the ice

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:13.319 align:middle line:90%
caps of the Earth.

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:15.980 align:middle line:84%
Every year, a new layer
of ice is deposited.

00:17:15.980 --> 00:17:17.839 align:middle line:84%
It captures air bubbles
of the atmosphere--

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:19.390 align:middle line:90%
dust, pollen grains.

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:22.510 align:middle line:84%
And when it freezes over, it
creates a permanent layer.

00:17:22.510 --> 00:17:26.240 align:middle line:84%
There is what we could think of
as a virtual library of Earth's

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:28.030 align:middle line:90%
history locked up in the poles.

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:31.679 align:middle line:84%
In 1999, the
scientists of the Earth

00:17:31.679 --> 00:17:33.470 align:middle line:84%
got together from many
different countries,

00:17:33.470 --> 00:17:37.380 align:middle line:84%
many different
scientific disciplines.

00:17:37.380 --> 00:17:40.850 align:middle line:84%
And they agreed to preserve as
much of this data as they could

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:43.479 align:middle line:84%
by drilling through the
deepest and the thickest part

00:17:43.479 --> 00:17:44.520 align:middle line:90%
of the ice in Antarctica.

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:47.010 align:middle line:84%
But even the
scientists were amazed

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:49.900 align:middle line:90%
at how much data was revealed.

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:52.500 align:middle line:84%
Each year is represented
by one layer of ice.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:56.960 align:middle line:84%
They drilled through over
420,000 layers of ice.

00:17:56.960 --> 00:18:00.860 align:middle line:84%
420,000 years of the
history of this planet.

00:18:00.860 --> 00:18:02.460 align:middle line:84%
We now have to
compare with where

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:04.220 align:middle line:84%
we are right now to
see if we are truly

00:18:04.220 --> 00:18:05.900 align:middle line:90%
living in an anomalous time.

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:08.300 align:middle line:84%
And this is what I'd like
to share with our viewers.

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:09.430 align:middle line:84%
If you've never
seen an ice core,

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:11.388 align:middle line:84%
I want you to see what
the ice cores look like.

00:18:11.388 --> 00:18:14.430 align:middle line:84%
You should be seeing them
on your screen right now.

00:18:14.430 --> 00:18:16.400 align:middle line:90%
This is part of an ice library.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:18.410 align:middle line:84%
And from these
ancient cores, we can

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:21.120 align:middle line:84%
discover ancient temperatures,
ancient sea levels,

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:23.210 align:middle line:84%
how strong the energy
from the sun was,

00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:26.470 align:middle line:84%
how strong the magnetic field
of the Earth was, so much more.

00:18:26.470 --> 00:18:30.790 align:middle line:84%
So the first graph of data
derived from the ice cores.

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:32.349 align:middle line:84%
You're looking at
it on your screen.

00:18:32.349 --> 00:18:33.890 align:middle line:84%
And it might look
a little technical.

00:18:33.890 --> 00:18:35.630 align:middle line:84%
But all I'd like for
you to see from this

00:18:35.630 --> 00:18:37.830 align:middle line:84%
is that, obviously,
cycles are present.

00:18:37.830 --> 00:18:39.950 align:middle line:84%
That's what we're
looking at here.

00:18:39.950 --> 00:18:41.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The up, down, up, down.

00:18:41.620 --> 00:18:44.510 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The present is on the
left-hand side of the screen.

00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:48.160 align:middle line:84%
450,000 years into the
past toward the right.

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:51.230 align:middle line:84%
The upper two graphs are
two different ice cores

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:53.850 align:middle line:84%
that actually track
one another in terms

00:18:53.850 --> 00:18:55.891 align:middle line:90%
of the ancient temperatures.

00:18:55.891 --> 00:18:57.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If you're
just a layman, you

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:59.230 align:middle line:84%
could see there's
a pattern here.

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:00.190 align:middle line:90%
There's a pattern.

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:02.860 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Every 100,000 years
roughly, there's a warming,

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:05.310 align:middle line:84%
and then followed
immediately by a cooling.

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:08.647 align:middle line:84%
The graph on the bottom is
showing the ice thickness.

00:19:08.647 --> 00:19:09.480 align:middle line:90%
It's very intuitive.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:13.330 align:middle line:84%
The ice thickness collapses when
the temperatures get warmer.

00:19:13.330 --> 00:19:15.960 align:middle line:84%
So when Earth heats
up, the ice melts.

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:18.380 align:middle line:84%
And when the temperatures
cool, then the ice

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:19.392 align:middle line:90%
becomes thicker again.

00:19:19.392 --> 00:19:20.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It makes sense.

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:20.660 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah.

00:19:20.660 --> 00:19:22.620 align:middle line:84%
This is what we're
seeing from this graph.

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:25.430 align:middle line:90%
Where we are is on the far left.

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:28.260 align:middle line:84%
And it is obvious that we
are in an upward surge, where

00:19:28.260 --> 00:19:30.550 align:middle line:84%
we would expect the
climate to be warming.

00:19:30.550 --> 00:19:32.520 align:middle line:84%
So Lisa, as a geologist,
what I can say to you

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:34.130 align:middle line:84%
is if Earth were
not experiencing

00:19:34.130 --> 00:19:36.370 align:middle line:84%
a little bit of warming
now, I'd be concerned

00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:38.490 align:middle line:84%
because I'd say
what's different now

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:40.764 align:middle line:84%
than there has been for
the last 450,000 years?

00:19:40.764 --> 00:19:41.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Based on the cycles.

00:19:41.930 --> 00:19:43.513 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Yeah, based
on these cycles.

00:19:43.513 --> 00:19:45.960 align:middle line:90%
What is it that's different now?

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:49.060 align:middle line:84%
This is probably the
most complex graph.

00:19:49.060 --> 00:19:50.790 align:middle line:84%
And it's one example
that I'd just

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:53.140 align:middle line:90%
like to share with our viewers.

00:19:53.140 --> 00:19:54.390 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to highlight in red.

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:56.500 align:middle line:90%
This is from the ice cores.

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:59.350 align:middle line:84%
What we're seeing in red,
this is the intensity

00:19:59.350 --> 00:20:00.606 align:middle line:90%
of the sun reaching the earth.

00:20:00.606 --> 00:20:02.980 align:middle line:84%
Now, I was a kid, I used to
think it was always the same.

00:20:02.980 --> 00:20:04.144 align:middle line:90%
Summertime, it's hot.

00:20:04.144 --> 00:20:05.060 align:middle line:90%
Wintertime, it's cold.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:07.535 align:middle line:84%
I grew up in Missouri, in
the Midwestern gray skies

00:20:07.535 --> 00:20:09.920 align:middle line:90%
of Missouri.

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:11.760 align:middle line:84%
As a geologist, what
I learned was nothing

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:13.430 align:middle line:90%
could be further from the truth.

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:15.590 align:middle line:84%
That there is a
tremendous variation.

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:17.940 align:middle line:84%
So we see the first
arrow I'm bringing up.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:18.850 align:middle line:90%
This is present time.

00:20:18.850 --> 00:20:20.100 align:middle line:90%
This is today.

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:22.350 align:middle line:84%
And you can see that we
are experiencing actually

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:24.650 align:middle line:90%
a little spike in the energy.

00:20:24.650 --> 00:20:29.010 align:middle line:90%
There's a little intense spike.

00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:32.460 align:middle line:84%
A greater intensity of
energy from the sun today.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:33.490 align:middle line:90%
Now the next arrow.

00:20:33.490 --> 00:20:36.040 align:middle line:90%
This is 5,000 years ago.

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:38.360 align:middle line:90%
This is one world age ago.

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:42.705 align:middle line:84%
1,872,000 days ago, there
was another little spike.

00:20:42.705 --> 00:20:44.080 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's a
lot of other stuff

00:20:44.080 --> 00:20:45.564 align:middle line:90%
I'm not even talking about here.

00:20:45.564 --> 00:20:47.730 align:middle line:84%
But what I'd like to call
your attention to is this.

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:49.690 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the
spike today, and you

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:53.537 align:middle line:84%
look at where it was 5,000 years
ago, they're almost identical.

00:20:53.537 --> 00:20:55.870 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to clean this up
so we can see it even better.

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:56.954 align:middle line:90%
Here it is.

00:20:56.954 --> 00:20:58.370 align:middle line:84%
Look at the top
of the green line.

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:01.435 align:middle line:84%
We are experiencing almost the
same intense energy of the sun

00:21:01.435 --> 00:21:02.900 align:middle line:90%
today as we were then.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:06.820 align:middle line:84%
Now let's extend it back another
5,000 years, another world age

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:09.810 align:middle line:84%
cycle, and we see that
10,000 years ago, it's

00:21:09.810 --> 00:21:11.010 align:middle line:90%
almost the same as well.

00:21:11.010 --> 00:21:12.485 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So why all the crisis?

00:21:12.485 --> 00:21:13.580 align:middle line:90%
Why all the--

00:21:13.580 --> 00:21:16.360 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well,
because if we are not

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:19.190 align:middle line:84%
accustomed to thinking
in terms of cycles.

00:21:19.190 --> 00:21:23.540 align:middle line:84%
When a scientist looks at 20
years, or 50 years, or 100,

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:26.414 align:middle line:84%
or 500 years, and sees
temperatures warming,

00:21:26.414 --> 00:21:27.080 align:middle line:90%
they're alarmed.

00:21:27.080 --> 00:21:28.204 align:middle line:90%
They say something's wrong.

00:21:28.204 --> 00:21:30.460 align:middle line:90%
It's all about context, Lisa.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:34.160 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not saying that
everything that we have done

00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:34.810 align:middle line:90%
is wrong.

00:21:34.810 --> 00:21:37.509 align:middle line:84%
And I'm certain that
the carbon dioxide

00:21:37.509 --> 00:21:39.550 align:middle line:84%
we're throwing in the
atmosphere is contributing.

00:21:39.550 --> 00:21:40.540 align:middle line:90%
It definitely is contributing.

00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:41.280 align:middle line:90%
Is it the cause?

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:42.970 align:middle line:90%
No, it cannot be.

00:21:42.970 --> 00:21:46.150 align:middle line:84%
Because we see these
cycles of warming

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:50.270 align:middle line:84%
450,000 years in the past,
before we had the industry--

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:50.927 align:middle line:90%
we believe.

00:21:50.927 --> 00:21:52.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we had
the industry then

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:54.650 align:middle line:84%
that we have now, or the number
of people and the populations.

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:56.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's usually
the contributing factor

00:21:56.300 --> 00:21:57.200 align:middle line:90%
in everything I hear.

00:21:57.200 --> 00:21:58.500 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah, it is.

00:21:58.500 --> 00:22:00.000 align:middle line:84%
So what we're seeing
now-- and this

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.560 align:middle line:84%
is one example of
the kind of data

00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:02.810 align:middle line:90%
that comes from the ice cores.

00:22:02.810 --> 00:22:05.610 align:middle line:84%
And I'm just using
this as one example.

00:22:05.610 --> 00:22:07.580 align:middle line:84%
What I've done is
I pulled together,

00:22:07.580 --> 00:22:10.830 align:middle line:84%
in the interest of time, many
different parameters from

00:22:10.830 --> 00:22:14.680 align:middle line:84%
the last two world age cycles,
from the last two 5,000-year

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:18.710 align:middle line:84%
cycles, averaging those together
so that we can really get

00:22:18.710 --> 00:22:21.500 align:middle line:84%
a handle-- are we
living a broken Earth?

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:23.570 align:middle line:84%
Are we living something
anomalous today?

00:22:23.570 --> 00:22:26.196 align:middle line:84%
And this is going to tell
the answer right here.

00:22:26.196 --> 00:22:27.320 align:middle line:90%
The categories on the left.

00:22:27.320 --> 00:22:29.820 align:middle line:84%
The magnetic strength
of the Earth.

00:22:29.820 --> 00:22:32.180 align:middle line:84%
Global warming,
the temperatures.

00:22:32.180 --> 00:22:35.670 align:middle line:84%
What's happening with the polar
ice, is it melting or growing.

00:22:35.670 --> 00:22:38.130 align:middle line:84%
And the intensity
of the sun's energy.

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:38.680 align:middle line:90%
Historically,

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:41.410 align:middle line:84%
in the last two cycles
that we're talking about

00:22:41.410 --> 00:22:43.589 align:middle line:84%
that the Mayans
identified, historically

00:22:43.589 --> 00:22:45.130 align:middle line:84%
the magnetic fields
of the Earth have

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:47.620 align:middle line:84%
been measured in
units called VADM.

00:22:47.620 --> 00:22:48.280 align:middle line:90%
Very technical.

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:50.280 align:middle line:84%
We don't even have to
worry about what it means.

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:52.140 align:middle line:84%
But they were
measured in numbers

00:22:52.140 --> 00:22:55.960 align:middle line:84%
that range from 5.5
to 10.5 on this scale.

00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:57.624 align:middle line:84%
Presently, we are
at 7.5, right--

00:22:57.624 --> 00:22:58.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right in the middle.

00:22:58.790 --> 00:23:01.050 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --where I
would expect us to be.

00:23:01.050 --> 00:23:02.150 align:middle line:90%
It is not anomalous.

00:23:02.150 --> 00:23:05.180 align:middle line:84%
We are right where we should be
for where we are in the cycle

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:05.960 align:middle line:90%
right now.

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:06.630 align:middle line:90%
Global warming.

00:23:06.630 --> 00:23:09.407 align:middle line:84%
Historically, the planet
rises 1 to 2 degrees Celsius,

00:23:09.407 --> 00:23:11.490 align:middle line:84%
depending on where you're
taking the measurements.

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:13.840 align:middle line:84%
This is approximately
where we are right now.

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:16.120 align:middle line:84%
We're averaging about 1
degree Celsius right now.

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:18.680 align:middle line:84%
Polar ice always melts
during the cycles.

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:21.050 align:middle line:84%
It's melting a lot
right now, that's true.

00:23:21.050 --> 00:23:23.125 align:middle line:90%
But we always expect it to melt.

00:23:23.125 --> 00:23:25.750 align:middle line:84%
It may be melting a little more
because we may have contributed

00:23:25.750 --> 00:23:27.740 align:middle line:84%
to the carbon dioxide
maybe a little more.

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:28.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:23:28.010 --> 00:23:28.400 align:middle line:90%
That's a fact.

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:30.210 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The sun's
energy always spikes.

00:23:30.210 --> 00:23:31.780 align:middle line:90%
And as we saw, the sharp rise.

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:33.650 align:middle line:84%
This is precisely
where we are right now.

00:23:33.650 --> 00:23:35.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the bottom
line is that most people

00:23:35.980 --> 00:23:38.320 align:middle line:90%
are looking back 100, 200 years.

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:40.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we're
seeing in the media.

00:23:40.070 --> 00:23:40.653 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yes.

00:23:40.653 --> 00:23:43.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: They're not
looking back 5,125 years.

00:23:43.130 --> 00:23:44.255 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Here's the thing.

00:23:44.255 --> 00:23:46.590 align:middle line:84%
Around 1880 is when consistent
records for the National

00:23:46.590 --> 00:23:47.950 align:middle line:90%
Weather Service began.

00:23:47.950 --> 00:23:51.210 align:middle line:84%
Many of the records are from
1880 until the year 2000.

00:23:51.210 --> 00:23:53.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, during that time
there has been a warming,

00:23:53.490 --> 00:23:55.910 align:middle line:84%
both of the ocean
and the atmosphere.

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:57.550 align:middle line:90%
It looks alarming by itself.

00:23:57.550 --> 00:24:01.420 align:middle line:84%
When you look at that within the
context of a world age cycle,

00:24:01.420 --> 00:24:02.930 align:middle line:90%
it suddenly is not alarming.

00:24:02.930 --> 00:24:03.890 align:middle line:90%
It fits right into the patterns.

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:04.210 align:middle line:90%
So it's about perspective.

00:24:04.210 --> 00:24:07.250 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so those records
indeed did not exist back then.

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:10.090 align:middle line:84%
However, we're learning that
from the polar ice caps.

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:11.160 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Precisely.

00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:14.420 align:middle line:84%
So the bottom line for
me is I am less concerned

00:24:14.420 --> 00:24:16.880 align:middle line:84%
about the physical changes
here on planet Earth.

00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:18.980 align:middle line:84%
The parameters that
we're seeing now--

00:24:18.980 --> 00:24:22.710 align:middle line:84%
barring some unforeseen event,
like an asteroid hitting

00:24:22.710 --> 00:24:26.090 align:middle line:84%
the Earth, or a super flare
from the sun, or something

00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:29.670 align:middle line:84%
like that-- the conditions-- the
physical conditions that we're

00:24:29.670 --> 00:24:32.950 align:middle line:84%
experiencing now are what
our ancestors experienced

00:24:32.950 --> 00:24:35.710 align:middle line:84%
5,000 years ago at
the end of their cycle

00:24:35.710 --> 00:24:39.700 align:middle line:84%
and 5,000 years ago at the
end of the one previous.

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:41.940 align:middle line:84%
I'm less concerned about
the physical changes, Lisa.

00:24:41.940 --> 00:24:44.000 align:middle line:84%
What I'm really
concerned about is us.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.210 align:middle line:84%
How do we treat one another
as we go through the changes?

00:24:47.210 --> 00:24:52.040 align:middle line:84%
How do we learn to work
together or to compete

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:55.490 align:middle line:84%
as we go through the diminishing
resources of fresh water

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:58.190 align:middle line:84%
and food as the
growing season changes,

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.830 align:middle line:84%
and our ability to feed an
ever-growing population.

00:25:01.830 --> 00:25:05.020 align:middle line:84%
E.O. Wilson, a Harvard
biologist-- E.O. Wilson, very,

00:25:05.020 --> 00:25:07.140 align:middle line:90%
very well known in his field.

00:25:07.140 --> 00:25:09.990 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like to
share a quote that he

00:25:09.990 --> 00:25:14.180 align:middle line:84%
has made about precisely how
unique this time in history is.

00:25:14.180 --> 00:25:16.097 align:middle line:84%
So you know that
it's not a Greggism.

00:25:16.097 --> 00:25:18.180 align:middle line:84%
E.O. Wilson is saying--
this is a quote-- he says,

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:21.990 align:middle line:84%
we're entering what he calls
a "bottleneck in time."

00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:22.990 align:middle line:90%
I love this imagery.

00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:24.700 align:middle line:90%
A bottleneck in time.

00:25:24.700 --> 00:25:28.470 align:middle line:84%
This narrow opening
"when our resources"--

00:25:28.470 --> 00:25:30.440 align:middle line:84%
so he's talking about
our emotional resources,

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:32.930 align:middle line:84%
our psychological resources,
our physical resources--

00:25:32.930 --> 00:25:35.750 align:middle line:84%
"and our ability to solve
our problems will be pushed

00:25:35.750 --> 00:25:36.560 align:middle line:90%
to their limits."

00:25:36.560 --> 00:25:40.030 align:middle line:84%
And I cannot help but think
we are at the point where

00:25:40.030 --> 00:25:41.810 align:middle line:84%
we're reaching many
of those limits now.

00:25:41.810 --> 00:25:45.250 align:middle line:84%
Again, this was 2005
was when he said this.

00:25:45.250 --> 00:25:47.870 align:middle line:84%
I think if you're watching
this program, every one of you

00:25:47.870 --> 00:25:50.270 align:middle line:84%
is going through
stuff right now.

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:52.490 align:middle line:84%
All of our lives
are being touched

00:25:52.490 --> 00:25:56.180 align:middle line:84%
by the economic collapse,
global economic collapse,

00:25:56.180 --> 00:25:59.740 align:middle line:84%
the disappearance of the ability
to grow and share food the way

00:25:59.740 --> 00:26:02.530 align:middle line:84%
we have in the
past, fresh water,

00:26:02.530 --> 00:26:05.760 align:middle line:84%
and changing in climate, how we
adapt to that climate change.

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:09.714 align:middle line:84%
All of those things are touching
every one of our lives in ways

00:26:09.714 --> 00:26:11.630 align:middle line:84%
maybe that we're only
beginning to understand.

00:26:11.630 --> 00:26:13.767 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Haven't those
civilizations 5,000 years ago

00:26:13.767 --> 00:26:15.100 align:middle line:90%
had to deal with the same thing?

00:26:15.100 --> 00:26:16.939 align:middle line:84%
But they didn't
have the population.

00:26:16.939 --> 00:26:19.480 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, this is a very
good question that I've asked.

00:26:19.480 --> 00:26:21.030 align:middle line:84%
I've said, what is the
difference between us

00:26:21.030 --> 00:26:21.630 align:middle line:90%
now and then?

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:23.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, certainly
ancient civilizations,

00:26:23.220 --> 00:26:24.070 align:middle line:90%
they had to deal with--

00:26:24.070 --> 00:26:25.195 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How did they do it?

00:26:25.195 --> 00:26:27.830 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --diminishing
firewood or when

00:26:27.830 --> 00:26:28.965 align:middle line:90%
the crops weren't growing.

00:26:28.965 --> 00:26:29.590 align:middle line:90%
The answer is--

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:30.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Famine.

00:26:30.470 --> 00:26:31.510 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yes, they did.

00:26:31.510 --> 00:26:33.810 align:middle line:84%
But never has a
single generation

00:26:33.810 --> 00:26:35.910 align:middle line:84%
of such technical
sophistication been

00:26:35.910 --> 00:26:38.870 align:middle line:84%
faced with so many
different crises all

00:26:38.870 --> 00:26:40.930 align:middle line:90%
in the same window of time.

00:26:40.930 --> 00:26:42.970 align:middle line:84%
And the experts
are telling us we

00:26:42.970 --> 00:26:44.730 align:middle line:84%
must solve these
very, very quickly.

00:26:44.730 --> 00:26:47.680 align:middle line:84%
In some cases, with the
economy and with the prospect

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:50.750 align:middle line:84%
of global war, we've got
about 12 to 18 months

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:52.310 align:middle line:84%
to figure out how
to deal with this.

00:26:52.310 --> 00:26:54.710 align:middle line:84%
That's not long to
change the way we think.

00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:57.530 align:middle line:84%
And this is precisely
what we're being told, is

00:26:57.530 --> 00:27:00.910 align:middle line:84%
that we must think differently
than we've ever thought before

00:27:00.910 --> 00:27:04.510 align:middle line:84%
and change our thinking
quickly to meet

00:27:04.510 --> 00:27:07.010 align:middle line:84%
the demands the crises are
placing upon our world.

00:27:07.010 --> 00:27:12.360 align:middle line:84%
The beauty and the good news
is that we have good, sound,

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:14.370 align:middle line:84%
scientific reasons to
change our thinking.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:16.410 align:middle line:84%
We don't have to
grasp at straws.

00:27:16.410 --> 00:27:19.060 align:middle line:84%
New discoveries that I'm going
to share in just a moment

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:21.980 align:middle line:84%
are giving us very good
reasons to change the way

00:27:21.980 --> 00:27:24.400 align:middle line:84%
we have been led to think
of ourselves in the past

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:28.660 align:middle line:84%
so that we may meet these
crises with new, life-affirming,

00:27:28.660 --> 00:27:31.080 align:middle line:90%
innovative solutions.

00:27:31.080 --> 00:27:34.210 align:middle line:84%
Not just to survive,
Lisa, but to transcend.

00:27:34.210 --> 00:27:36.372 align:middle line:84%
To become better people,
better communities.

00:27:36.372 --> 00:27:38.830 align:middle line:84%
To create a better world than
we had going into the crisis.

00:27:38.830 --> 00:27:41.030 align:middle line:84%
And that is why I'm so
passionate about what

00:27:41.030 --> 00:27:41.530 align:middle line:90%
we're doing.

00:27:41.530 --> 00:27:43.238 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I so
appreciate everything

00:27:43.238 --> 00:27:45.670 align:middle line:84%
you're doing to bring this
to a broader audience.

00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:46.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And your
information as well.

00:27:46.820 --> 00:27:48.444 align:middle line:84%
That is what needs
to happen right now.

00:27:48.444 --> 00:27:49.500 align:middle line:90%
And we're all feeling.

